    "questionText": "Two cards are drawn at random from a pack of 52 cards. What is the probability that either both are black or both are queens?",
    "questionType": "mcq",
    "options": ["A) $\\dfrac{55}{221}$", "B) $\\dfrac{325}{1326}$", "C) $\\dfrac{6}{1326}$", "D) $\\dfrac{1}{221}$"],
    "correctAnswer": "A) $\\dfrac{55}{221}$",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "solution": {
      "steps": [
        {
          "stepNumber": 1,
          "explanation": "Find total ways to draw 2 cards from 52.",
          "formula": null,
          "formulaExpression": "n(S) = \\binom{52}{2} = \\dfrac{52 \\times 51}{2} = 1326",
          "calculation": "n(S) = 1326",
          "result": "n(S) = 1326"
        },
        {
          "stepNumber": 2,
          "explanation": "Let A = both cards black (26 black cards). Find n(A).",
          "formula": null,
          "formulaExpression": "n(A) = \\binom{26}{2} = \\dfrac{26 \\times 25}{2} = 325",
          "calculation": "n(A) = 325",
          "result": "n(A) = 325"
        },
        {
          "stepNumber": 3,
          "explanation": "Let B = both cards queens (4 queens). Find n(B) and n(A ∩ B) = both black queens (2 black queens).",
          "formula": null,
          "formulaExpression": "n(B) = \\binom{4}{2} = 6, \\quad n(A \\cap B) = \\binom{2}{2} = 1",
          "calculation": "n(B) = 6, n(A∩B) = 1",
          "result": "n(B) = 6, n(A∩B) = 1"
        },
        {
          "stepNumber": 4,
          "explanation": "Apply addition rule of probability.",
          "formula": null,
          "formulaExpression": "P(A \\cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \\cap B) = \\dfrac{325}{1326} + \\dfrac{6}{1326} - \\dfrac{1}{1326} = \\dfrac{330}{1326} = \\dfrac{55}{221}",
          "calculation": "(325 + 6 - 1)/1326 = 330/1326 = 55/221",
          "result": "$\\dfrac{55}{221}$"
        }
      ],
      "shortcut": "Use P(A∪B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A∩B); black queens = 2 (queen of spades and clubs).",
